R Data Training: Part 1

The Data Community

September 2021

Introduction

This is a training course to teach the basics of how to work with data efficiently in R.

The course will be divided into 3 parts:

  • Part 1: Importing and viewing data, and introduction to data types
  • Part 2: Manipulating data and an introduction to tidy data and R workflows
  • Part 3: Data visualisation and the final project

This training course is loosely based on this Data Carpentry course.

Aims

This course is designed to provide you with the tools you need to learn how to work with data in R. In particular.

  • Demonstrate how R can allow you to do things more efficiently (i.e. make your life easier)
  • Explain when R can be particularly powerful relative to other tools (such as Excel or Tableau)
  • Provide you with a basic understanding of how to work with data in R
  • Provide you with the tool kit to build on that basic understanding of R

This course is not going to teach you R (sorry). That takes time and practice, much like learning a foreign language, which we don’t have. Rather, we want to teach you the methods that should help you quickly get answers to your problems and save hours of wasted time and frustration.

To take a cooking analogy, we don’t want to teach you how to cook. We want to teach you the basics of cooking (how to boil water, how to whisk etc), but more importantly we want to teach you how to use a recipe book (and point you to some good ones) and we want to show you some common mistakes that people make, how to recognise them and how to quickly resolve them.

The learning curve will be steep. If you have never used an analytical programming language before, certain ways of doing things may seem strange and/or not intuitive. You will, at some point, spend hours perplexed by some bug that will be simply resolved by the addition or removal of some minor character. It will at times be very frustrating. Don’t worry. This is normal. It happens to everyone including me. So be patient!

However, the benefits of persevering are huge. You will be able to do things that previously took days in seconds or even at the click of a button. You will also be able to work with datasets far greater in size than you have ever worked with before and take advantage of many of the developments in data infrastructure currently going on at the Bank. You will also be the proud owner of an increasingly valued skillset, not just within the Bank, but also externally. Finally, this whole process will might be fun. Learning a new skill should be.

When to use R (rather than Excel)

R is not always the right solution, and there are going to be times when Excel still is the easiest and quickest way to get things done. However, there are a number of circumstances where the benefits of R are likely to be most acute:

  1. Any analysis you need to run on multiple occasions will be more efficient in R. This includes “ad-hoc” reports, which we inevitably end up running on multiple occasions and/or converting into repeated reports.
  2. If you spend your time thinking: “I wish there was a function for this” in excel. In R there is a function for that.
  3. If proving the provenance of your results is important. In R you can make your full analysis, from the sourcing of data to the production of a polished presentation or document self contained. You can publish the full story.
  4. If you are working with data that is more than a couple of hundred rows.
  5. You are working with multiple related tables or tables from multiple sources.

How to make the most of this course

Don’t worry if you miss things, or don’t follow everything.

We are going to go quite quickly. You don’t need to memorize the name of every function you see. Instead, see and remember what is possible to do in R, while thinking about how you might solve problems in R. Finally, and most usefully, learn how to look for help when you face problems.

Quick recap of pre-session material

In the pre-session material you should have learnt how to install R, create a new project and install certain packages.

Let’s start by opening up your R project.

Click File > Open Project in R Studio and choose your project. Or, if it’s a recent project, you can do File > Recent Project.

Now we’re inside our R project, it’s time to start a new script. Click File > New File > R Script (or, Ctrl+Shift+N) to open one. You can go ahead and give the script a name (it will currently be “untitled”) by saving it (hit the “save” button from the tool-bar above your script (or, yet another short-cut - Ctrl+S).

At the top of our script, we should load all our package needs using library. First, we should load readr, dplyr, tidyr, stringr and ggplot2 (all from the tidyverse which you installed pre-session), as well as readxl, lubridate and boeCharts. We will need to call on these later.

Add the following commands up top in your script:

library(readr) # Reading csv
library(dplyr) # Manipulating data 
library(tidyr) # Create 'tidy' data
library(stringr) # Working with strings
library(ggplot2) # Creating charts
library(readxl) # Reading excel
library(lubridate) # Working with dates
library(boeCharts) # Formatting charts in Bank style

N.B. you can change the appearance of R Studio - this might be why your colleague’s version looks odd. Go to Tools > Global Options > Appearance to explore some customisation options.

Demo of end-to-end process

To demonstrate how useful (and quick!) R can be we’re going to start with the demo of a short end-to-end process.

The example is based on GDP output data from the ONS, with a focus on the impact of Covid across different sectors of the economy. What we’re going to show is how in just a short piece of code you can read in a dataset, manipulate it for analysis, and then chart your results. Don’t worry about following this piece of code now, as we’ll go through each of the steps slowly over the course of the three sessions.

In order to execute (or ‘run’) this code in an R script, we use Ctrl+Enter to run the current line or a selection (i.e. highlighted code). The R Studio cheat sheet is a useful reference for more shortcuts and tips.

First lets run the code that reads in the data and manipulates it for charting:

# Read in data
data <- read_excel("../data/GDPOutputData.xlsx", sheet = "Data")
sectors <- read_csv("../data/Sectors.csv")

# Manipulate data
data_sectors <- data %>% 
  select(any_of(c("Date", "TOTAL", sectors$Code))) %>% # selecting only columns that correspond to one of the sector codes
  mutate(DE = D + E) %>% # create a new column that is the sum of columns D & E 
  pivot_longer(-Date, names_to = "Code", values_to = "Level", ) %>% # convert into long dataset
  left_join(sectors, by = "Code", all.x = TRUE) %>% # merge with sector list to get the full names of sectors 
  select(Date, Code, Sector, Level) %>% # reorder columns 
  arrange(Code, Date) %>% # arrange by sector code and date
  filter(!Code %in% c("A", "D", "E", "T")) %>% # filter out a couple of sectors
  mutate(Sector = case_when(
    Code == "TOTAL" ~ "total", # Add in a sector name for the total
    Code == "DE" ~ "utilities", # Add in a sector name for the sum of D & E
    TRUE ~ str_to_lower(Sector))) %>%  # Convert all sector names to lower case 
  group_by(Code) %>% # group by code,
  mutate(Date = as.Date(Date), # make sure our Date column is a Date format
         QoQ = Level/lag(Level, 1)*100-100, # Create series for quarterly growth 
         YoY = Level/lag(Level, 4)*100-100, # Create series for year-on-year growth
         PreCovChg = Level/Level[Date == "2019-12-31"]*100-100) # create series to look at the change since pre-covid level (2019Q4)

Now let’s do some plots.

We might be interested in looking at a long run series of year-on-year growth across sectors to get a sense of how volatile they are in usual times and how the latest episode compares:

# Plot year-on-year growth for all sectors over time (standard R formatting)
ggplot(data = data_sectors, # set the dataset
       mapping = aes(x = Date, y = YoY, colour = Sector)) + # set the variables for the x and y axis, and choose to colour the lines by sector
  geom_line(na.rm = TRUE) + # choose a line graph and remove NA values (to avoid a warning given we have some NAs at the start) 
  facet_wrap( ~ Sector, scales = "free_y", ncol = 3, labeller = labeller(Sector = label_wrap_gen(35)))+ # create individual charts for each Sector, letting R choose the appropriate y axis scale for each one, and wrapping the sector titles
  labs(y = "Year-on-Year Growth, %") + # label the y axis (otherwise it would be the name of the y variable  - YoY)
  theme(legend.position = "none")

We then might want to zoom in on the first quarter of the pandemic to easily compare across the impact on different sectors:

# Plot QoQ growth in 20Q2 across sectors (MPR formatting)
data_sectors %>% # set the dataset
  filter(Date == as.Date("2020-06-30")) %>% # filter for only 20Q2 data points
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = QoQ, y = reorder(Sector, QoQ))) + # set the variables for the x and y axis 
  geom_col() + # choose a column chart
  labs(title = str_wrap("The pandemic hit consumer-facing services the hardest", 30),
       caption = "Source: ONS",
       y = "", 
       x = "Quarterly growth in 20Q2, %")+ # set axis labels and add a title and caption
  theme_mpr(plot_title_size = 13) # choose the MPR formatting theme

And we also might be interested in how things have evolved since then - have most sectors recovered to pre-covid levels by now?

# Plot cumulative % change since 19Q4/Pre-Covid (Bank Overground formatting)
data_sectors %>% # set the dataset
  filter(Date >= "2019-12-31") %>% # filter for data points from 19Q4 onwards 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = as.Date(Date), y = PreCovChg)) + # set the variables for the x and y axis
  geom_line() + # choose a line chart
  facet_wrap( ~ Sector, scales = "free_y", ncol = 2, labeller = labeller(Sector = label_wrap_gen(35)))+ # create individual charts for each sector, with 3 columns of charts and wrap sector titles
  labs(title = "Output remains below pre-pandemic levels across the majority of sectors",
       caption = "Source: ONS",
       y = "Percentage change vs 2019 Q4", 
       x = "Date")+ # set axis labels and add a title and caption
  scale_x_date(breaks = as.Date(data_sectors$Date), date_labels = "%b%y")+ # change the format of the date x axis  
  theme_overground(base_size = 10, plot_title_size = 12, strip_text_size = 10, caption_size = 10) # set the Bank overground formatting theme and adjust font size

Importing data

Pretty much everything you do in R will begin with some type of data. Most of the time you will be getting data into R from the outside, for example in .xlsx or .csv files.

We will be using the readr and readxl packages which we loaded at the start of the R session. (A cheat sheet is here).

Next, we should locate the data to read in. At this stage, check you have a copy of the file GDPoutputdata.xlsx and Sectors.csv in your project folder, viewable in the Files “pane” (bottom-right window of R Studio), preferable nested in a /data sub-folder.

At this point, we must locate the readr function that aligns with the file-type we’re working with. All of this package’s functions for reading data have a read_ prefix, followed by some indication of the file format.

In our case, we should plump for the read_csv() edition. The simplest application of this function demands a single argument - the path to your data. Let’s try reading in the Sectors.csv dataset:

read_csv("data/Sectors.csv")

Tip: Entering filepaths is tedious. You can save time and avoid spelling mistakes by pressing the ‘tab’ key when your cursor is in-between ‘empty’ speech-marks, inside your ‘read’ function call e.g. read_csv(""). You should see a ‘file explorer’ popup, which lets you navigate to your desired file using additional ‘tab’ strokes while constructing the filepath for you simultaneously.

Running the read_csv() command with a file-path to the Sectors dataset produces a tabular data frame object in our R session. However, at the moment this object is not stored for later use. If we want to make this data available to us for later (e.g. for data manipulation or visualisation) we must give it a name.

In Excel, the process of assigning names to values or objects is done for us. When we type the value “foo” into the cell “A1”, the value “foo” is now assigned to the name “A1”. We can refer to “foo” indirectly by typing A1 as the argument to a formula in any other cell. We can see which values are assigned to which name by simply looking at the cell reference of the corresponding value.

In R we have to name all our objects, or variables, explicitly. We do so by assigning the value to a name. Object names can be pretty much anything we like (see ?make.names for the few restrictions) though typically it’s useful to pick a variable name that describes the value it refers to.

Tip: Pick names that are concise and meaningful i.e. describe the value referred to, and use only lowercase letters, numbers, and underscores (_). Use the tidyverse style guide for more advice on object names.

To name a value in R we use the assignment operator <-. The short-cut for the assignment operator is Alt + -. Be careful not to double the dash when typing <- otherwise you will get a particularly exotic and indecipherable R error - “invalid argument to unary operator”.

Tip: Try to use shortcuts for generating common operators like this. It will save you time and reduce errors in your code caused by spelling mistakes.

Let’s re-run the read_csv() command, but this time assign the result to the name Sectors:

sectors <- read_csv("data/Sectors.csv")

If you go to you environment pane (top right-hand window of R studio) you will now see an object called Sectors which R tells us has 20 observations “obs.” of 2 variables.

Now, we can access the data object within our R session by simply referring to it by name:

A lot of the time at the Bank we also work with data stored in excel files. The approach for loading these data is very similar as the csv example we just looked at, but we use the read_excel() command from the readxl package instead. One notable difference is that excel files can have multiple sheets and so we need to tell R which sheets we want to load in.

Let’s load in the GDP Output data now from the excel file. We can also assign variables to names using =.

data = read_excel("data/GDPOutputData.xlsx", sheet = "Data")

Function arguments

In the read_excel function above, we needed to tell R both the filepath of the excel file and the sheet. These two elements are referred to as function arguments. In R (as in Excel), function arguments have a default order.

read_excel() takes a number of different arguments, of which we’ve used two here: path, and sheet:

  • The first parameter in the example above "data/GDPOutputData.xlsx", is passed to the argument path
  • The second parameter, "Data", is passed to the argument sheet

Tip: Sometimes you can’t remember which arguments are need for the function to work, or which order they go in. To check, either go to help pages for the function by typing ?functionname or by pressing tab inside the function parentheses.

So we can call the read_excel function in a number of ways…

read_excel(path = "data/GDPOutputData.xlsx", sheet = "Data")

read_excel("../data/GDPOutputData.xlsx", "Data", range = "A1:D100")

A quick detour: Tab complete

Working in R studio or almost any other computing or scripting application, tab is one of the most useful and powerful keys on your keyboard. Learning to use tab is going to save huge amounts of time and effort, as well as avoiding frustration caused by spelling mistakes and finding bugs in case-sensitive code.

Let’ start by typing r and pressing tab. R studio provides an alphabetic list of all the objects that start with s in their name. We can scroll down the list using our up and down keys. Functions have are marked by a blue bar. Alongside the names of functions, R will also provide some information about what that function does and how it works.

Now let’s type e and press tab again. The list is now restricted to objects that start with the letters “re”. To choose the function read_csv, with the function read_csv selected, we once again press tab. R studio will auto complete the word “read_csv” and place your cursor between the parentheses, ready to begin typing the arguments for your function.

If we press Esc to clear our console and type Read_ex into the console and press tab. This time R does not give you any options, but auto-completes to read_excel() straight away. This is because the function read_excel() is the only function or object that matches the pattern “read_ex”. (Note that R studio also converts your capital “R” to the lower case “r” needed for the function. R is case-sensitive, so using tab will ensure you don’t have to worry about this).

If you start typing the name of an object that is not available such as rez and press tab, R studio will tell you that object does not exist with the warning (no matches). Therefore using tab should help you pick up spelling mistakes in your code.

N.B. the power of tab auto complete doesn’t just exist for functions and in the console, but for all objects and also when writing commands in the script editor too.

Tip: If we are not sure how a function works we can press F1 (or Fn + F1, on laptops) when the cursor is in the function name, or type ?functionname into the console. This will bring up the help menu. For instance, to get help on the read_excel function, type ?read_excel

Data types

In R, much like in excel and all other programming languages, data is stored and categorised in data types, like numbers, text and dates. These data types constrain what functions will work on which data. One of the most common error messages you will see will be caused by attempting to apply a function to data of a data type that is not compatible with that function.

This is generally a good thing. Since it will stop us from doing things that don’t make sense, like trying to sum a word sum("hello").

However, sometimes it makes life a bit complicated. For instance, how do we differentiate between numbers that are numbers…

1
## [1] 1

…and numbers that we want to be interpreted as text (or “strings” in R language)?

"1"
## [1] "1"

The way to discover data types is to use the class function.

Let’s use class on the number 1:

class(1)
## [1] "numeric"

Let’s use class on the string "1":

class("1")
## [1] "character"

We can specifically test is something if is numeric or a character datatype using the is.<insert_datatype> family of functions. For instance:

is.numeric(1.44)
## [1] TRUE
is.character("hello")
## [1] TRUE

We can actually change the datatype using the as.<insert_datatype> family of functions. For example, R treats all numbers as numeric by default. If we want to treat them as integers, we can use the as.integer() function to cast them to the integer datatype.

as.integer(10)
## [1] 10

Let’s have a look at the data types in our datasets.

First, less check what class the TOTAL column in our data table is:

class(data$TOTAL)
## [1] "numeric"

Unsuprisingly, it’s numeric given it refers to the total output of the UK economy in £bn.

Now let’s check the class of the Sector column in our sectors table:

class(sectors$Sector)
## [1] "character"

It’s a character as it includes the names of the various sectors.

Strings

As well as working with numeric data, R has lots of functions for working with text (in computer speak, commonly called strings). Strings (or text) in R are also called characters.

R comes pre-packaged with some functions useful for working with strings. However, we are going to use a package of string functions called stringr, which you should have installed already.

If you haven’t already, make the functions in stringr available to your R session by using the library function:

library(stringr)

As in Excel, we tell R that something is a string by putting it in quotation marks. Equally, R tells us that the output of something is a string by putting it in quotation marks.

R has two types of quotation marks for denoting strings.

"hello"
## [1] "hello"
'hello'
## [1] "hello"

This allows us to use quotation marks inside our strings, if we want:

"hello 'world'"
## [1] "hello 'world'"

The package stringr provides lots of nice functions for working with strings, which are described in your stringr cheatsheet (an online edition can be found here).

Many common string functions in Excel have equivalents inside stringr. For instance, in our demo at the start we converted the sector names to lower case using str_to_lower:

str_to_lower(sectors$Sector)
##  [1] "agriculture, forestry and fishing"                                                               
##  [2] "mining and quarrying"

Dates

We have one more type of data in our datasets that we haven’t talked about yet. Let’s look at the class of the Date column in our data table:

class(data$Date)
## [1] "POSIXct" "POSIXt"

Perhaps not what you were expecting!

POSIXct is a date-time object, that stores both a date and time with an associated time zone. The default time zone selected is the time zone that your computer is set to which is most often your local time zone. POSIXct stores date and time in seconds with the number of seconds beginning at 1 January 1970.

When working with dates, it’s highly recommended to use the lubridate package. The lubridate cheatsheet can be found here.

Load the lubridate package if you haven’t already:

library(lubridate)

Tip: when you type a function name and press tab, RStudio will also tell you which package that function comes from. R, by default, loads functions from the packages base, utils, methods, stats, graphics, grdevices upon startup.

lubridate contains some nice functions for telling us about the current date. For example, now() tells us the time:

now()
## [1] "2021-09-01 11:02:05 BST"

It’s very common when we load a new dataset that our date functions won’t work because R has stored those dates as text (or “strings”), and so we often need to convert the series to dates explicitly. R (and most analytical programming languages) is particularly cautious about automatically converting dates that could be stored in a multitude of ways e.g. “dd/mm/yy” or “yyyy/mm/dd”.

This will cause some strange and wonderful errors that may not be intuitive at first:

floor_date("01/01/2017")
## Error in UseMethod("reclass_date", orig): no applicable method for 'reclass_date' applied to an object of class "character"

So when we work with dates that are stored as strings, we need to convert them to dates before using date functions. lubridate has some very powerful intuitive functions to do that.

These functions have been very cleverly named. In order to work out the function name you need follow two steps.

  1. Identify the presence and order of year (y), month (m), day (d), hour (h), minute (m) and second (s) elements in your dates

  2. Use a lubridate function whose name replicates the abbreviated order. Each accepts a wide variety of input formats.

For instance, dates stored in the format “dd/mm/yyyy” are of the order day (d), month (m), year (y) and so can easily be converted to dates using a function called dmy:

dmy("01/01/2021")
## [1] "2021-01-01"

Let’s use class to check that this is indeed in date format now:

class("01/01/2021")
## [1] "character"
class(dmy("01/01/2021"))
## [1] "Date"

Note this also works for dates written in different forms.

dmy("01 Jan 2021")
## [1] "2021-01-01"

Tip: always enter and save dates in the format “yyyy-mm-dd”. This is the ISO standard date format (ISO-8601). Doing so should prevent problems with your computing incorrectly interpreting your dates. This allows us to use the as.Date() function from the package base.

Lets use as.Date()to turn the date column in our GDP dataset into a “Date” format (Note we can do this as it was already a date-time object)

data$Date <- as.Date(data$Date)

You may have spotted that we use this command when manipulating the data in the demo at the start, within the mutate function. You’ll find out more about manipulating data in the next session.

We can also change the format of those dates, for example for use in a Chart, using the format() function from the package base. Let’s say we wanted them in the form “01 Jan 2021” as above:

We might sometimes want to do maths with dates, for example to find out the number of days/months between two dates or to count forward/backward from a given date. lubridate has some powerful functions for doing this.

As an example, the MPC’s forecast always goes out 3 years from the quarter in which it is published. Rather than having to tell R the start and end date each time, we could therefore just give it the start date and let it work out the end date itself.

Let’s take the August 2021 forecast as an example (using the end of Q3 as the start date):

start <- as_date("2021-09-30")
end <- start + years(3)
start
## [1] "2021-09-30"
end
## [1] "2024-09-30"

If we know that the start date is always going to be the end of the current quarter we can also use the now() command, combined with lubridate’s ceiling_date() function to round up to the end of the quarter.

start <- as.Date(ceiling_date(now(), unit = "quarter"))
end <- start + years(3)
start
## [1] "2021-09-30"
end
## [1] "2024-09-30"

So now we don’t need to input anything ourselves and R will be able to figure out what the start and end date of the forecast should be each round. Very handy for automating processes!

The irregularity of the number of days in a month can make doing maths with dates more complicated. For instance, how do we get one month forward from 31 January? If lubridate is not sure what the answer should be, it will return NA:

jan31 <- as_date("2021-01-31")
jan31 + months(1)
## [1] NA

lubridate has some nifty operators to help with this. %m+% will roll imaginary dates (e.g. February 31st) to the last day of the previous month:

jan31 %m+% months(1)
## [1] "2021-02-28"

Logical

The final data type we are going to talk about is the logical data type. This is also commonly known as the boolean data type.

Values that are logical data types can either be TRUE, FALSE or NA. NA means that the value is ambiguous as to whether it is true or false (NA is also how R represents missing values - think back to when we looked at the structure of our data object and the result for the column referring to industry ‘07’).

Logical values are typically created as the output of some function or operator.

For instance, checking if 1 is more than (>) 2:

1 > 2
## [1] FALSE

To determine whether two values or variables are equal to each other, we use the equality (==), operator:

10 == 10
## [1] TRUE

This operator allows us to differentiate between:

  • Asking whether two variables are equal (==)
  • Assigning a name to a value (=).

Tip: Be careful when testing the equality of things. Remember to use two equals signs ==, otherwise you may not get the result you expect.

We may also want to test the inverse of some of these operators. For example, is 10 not equal to 10?

In R, this inverse (or not) operator is the exclamation mark (!). We can use it to test the inverse of equality:

10 != 10
## [1] FALSE

It can also be used in-front of certain functions to invert them:

!is.character(5)
## [1] TRUE

Learning and trouble shooting

Where to ask for help

There will be times when you code doesn’t work and you cannot understand why. It will be tempting to spend hours Googling and straining to solve your issue. Do not do this. If you are stuck for more than 15 minutes, either go away, do something else and come back, or find help:

  1. Google (with care). Links to stack overflow are often very helpful.
  2. Ask a colleague
  3. Ask a question on the Bank’s data community - check out why to join and how to use
  4. Look up a relevant tutorial

An important disclaimer

In any tool that you use to work with data (for instance excel) there are always a large number of different ways to solve a problem. This is even more true for analytical programming languages such as R.

The methods taught in this class are one way to solve problems in R. There are also other ways. This you will quickly discover when you start to Google your problems. To a certain extent, how you solve a problem doesn’t matter, as long as the answer is correct.

That being said, we are teaching you in a way that follows the principles of something called the tidyverse. In essence we hope this means that you:

  • see intuitive examples
  • produce code that is easier to understand
  • possess code that is more compatible and robust to the latest developments in R
